'''Attina Marie Cannaday''' (born September 8, 1965) was charged with robbery, kidnapping, and homicide. At the time of her trial, she was a sixteen-year-old divorcee, who had married at thirteen and divorced at fourteen. She was convicted in Harrison County Circuit Court of the kidnap and murder of [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] Sergeant Ronald Wojcik and the jury sentenced her to death by lethal injection. The guilty verdict was upheld, but the sentence was reversed in 1984, Cannaday v. State, 455 So.2d 713, 720 (Miss. 1984), and she was resentenced to one life sentence and two 25-year sentences at [[Central Mississippi Correctional Facility]] (inmate number 42451).<ref>{{cite news |title=Laurel Leader Call Newspaper Archives, Defendant Watched The Events |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/laurel-leader-call-sep-23-1982-p-8/ |accessdate=27 July 2018 |work=Associated Press |agency=Laurel Leader Call (Newspaper) |publisher=NewspaperArchive.com |date=23 September 1982 |location=GULFPORT, Miss. |page=8 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Attina Marie CANNADAY v. STATE of Mississippi. |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=1084758817751911268&hl=en&as_sdt=2&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr |website=scholar.google.com |publisher=Supreme Court of Mississippi |accessdate=27 July 2018 |pages=715-727 |date=16 May 1984}}</ref> She was released on parole on March 9, 2008.<ref name="Baker">{{cite book |last1=Baker |first1=David V. |title=Women and Capital Punishment in the United States: An Analytical History |date=2015 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786499502 |pages=260-261 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QKUHCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA260&lpg=PA260&dq=Attina+Marie+Cannaday&source=bl&ots=aqzPlcBOzM&sig=jbdlwBqoeKp7uLXoso7xOCZJQcA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjL5c7P87_cAhUIllQKHSU1Bc04ChDoATALegQIBhAB#v=onepage&q=Attina%20Marie%20Cannaday&f=false |accessdate=27 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Valencia County">{{cite news |last1=Dendinger |first1=Julia M. |title=Belen High School students hear real stories about dangers of DWI |url=http://www.news-bulletin.com/news/belen-high-school-students-hear-real-stories-about-dangers-of/article_0349fbd6-09a3-11e7-a7c1-a33428403ee8.html |accessdate=6 August 2018 |work=Staff |publisher=Valencia County News-Bulletin |date=21 March 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610221019/http://www.news-bulletin.com/news/belen-high-school-students-hear-real-stories-about-dangers-of/article_0349fbd6-09a3-11e7-a7c1-a33428403ee8.html |archivedate=10 June 2017 |location=Belen, New Mexico |language=en |quote=She was paroled in 2008 and now reports regularly to the New Mexico Adult Probation and Parole Department.}}</ref>
The movie ''[[Too Young to Die?]]'' was very loosely based on her crimes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Crazy Lifetime Movies That Are Actually Based On True Stories |url=https://www.refinery29.com/2015/09/93353/lifetime-movies-based-on-true-stories#slide-43 |accessdate=27 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Today's birthday, June 21 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/aap/article-2660835/Todays-birthday-June-21.html |accessdate=27 July 2018 |work=Australian Associated Press |agency=Mail Online |publisher=ww.dailymail.co.uk |date=17 June 2014 |language=en |quote=The movie was loosely based on the true story of Attina Marie Cannaday, a runaway who...}}</ref>
