'''Bernal'''('''do''') '''de Bonaval'''('''le'''), also known as '''Bernardo '''('''de''')''' Bonaval''', was a 13th-century [[troubadour]] in the [[Kingdom of Galicia]] (in the northwest of the [[Iberian Peninsula]], in parts of modern Portugal and Spain) who wrote in the [[Galician-Portuguese]] language.

==Biography==
Little is known for certain about Bernal's background, life, or career.

Sources say that he was a native of [[Santiago de Compostela]],<ref name=AG /><ref name=GEC /> which is in the modern Spanish [[Province of A Coruña]]. He mentions a place called "Bonaval" in several of his poems.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jscholarship.library.jhu.edu/bitstream/handle/1774.2/33843/4-cantigas%20d%27amigo301-400.pdf?sequence=23&isAllowed=y |title=500 ''Cantigas d'Amigo'' |website=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |pages=361–368 |accessdate=18 September 2017}} The original Galician-Portuguese texts of Bernal's eight surviving ''cantigas d'amigo'', with scholarly notes.</ref> It has been suggested that he was born outside the mediaeval city walls of Santiago, because "de Bonaval" may refer to the [[Convent of San Domingos de Bonaval]], which is outside those walls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cantigas.fcsh.unl.pt/autor.asp?cdaut=22 |title=Bernal de Bonaval |website=[[Faculty of Social and Human Sciences]], [[Universidade Nova de Lisboa]] |language=[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] |accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> It has also been suggested that "Bernal de Bonaval" and (in Latin) "Frater Bernardus, prior Bone Uallis" ("Brother Bernardus, [[prior]] of Bone Uallis") may have been one and the same. If that suggestion is correct, then Bernal may have been a [[friar]] in the [[Dominican Order]], and "de Bonaval" may refer to the [[convent]] rather than to his birthplace.<ref name="Souto Cabo" />

He was active in the 13th century. Some sources suggest that he may have been born in the 12th century. He was known at the courts of [[Fernando III]] and [[Alfonso X]] (kings of Galicia 1231-1252 and 1252-1284 respectively).<ref name=AG>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoresgalegos.org/web/asp/contenido.asp?seccInt=3&letra=B&idAutor=257 |title=Bernal de Bonaval |website=autoresgalegos.org |language=[[Galician language|Galician]] |accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=GEC>{{cite web |url=http://www.enciclopedia.cat/EC-GEC-0011089.xml |title=Bernal de Bonaval |website=[[Gran Enciclopèdia Catalana]] |language=[[Catalan language|Catalan]] |accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://csm.mml.ox.ac.uk/index.php?p=bib_view&rec=159 |title=''Cantigas de Santa Maria'' Database |website=[[Oxford University]] |accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref>

A poem of 1266 by King Alfonso X directed at the troubadour {{ill|Pero da Ponte|es}} mentions Bernal: "''Vós nom trobades come proençal, / mais come Bernaldo de Bonaval; / por ende nom é trobar natural / pois que o del e do dem'aprendestes''"<ref name="Souto Cabo" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cantigas.fcsh.unl.pt/cantiga.asp?cdcant=491&pv=sim |title= Afonso X |website=Cantigas Medievais Galego-Portuguesas |language=[[Galician language|Galician]] |accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://culturafm.cmais.com.br/radiometropolis/lavra/bernal-de-bonaval-a-dona-que-eu-am-e-tenho |title=Bernal de Bonaval: A dona que eu am'e tenho |first=Fábio |last=Malavoglia |website=culturafm.cmais.com.br |language=[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] |date=26 August 2014 |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j0U08htguPUC&pg=PA225&lpg=PA225&dq=bernardo+bonaval&source=bl&ots=DmdSfr7ovE&sig=wJQudvfiEfcfs9tj2VYysOYtWGQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTi5rsqbfWAhVbFMAKHf0uBxAQ6AEIiwEwFA#v=onepage&q=bernardo%20bonaval&f=false |title=Alfonso X, the Learned: A Biography |first=H. Salvador |last=Martínez |others=Translated by Odile Cisneros |publisher=[[Brill Publishers|Brill]] |date=2 March 2010 |page=225 |isbn=978-9004181472 |accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref> ("You do not compose like a [[Provence|Provençal]] / but like Bernaldo de Bonaval / and therefore your poetry-making is not natural / for you learned it from him and from the [D]evil").<ref name=QI>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uvD-3ND91D4C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Queer Iberia: Sexualities, Cultures, and Crossings from the Middle Ages to the Renaissance |editor-first1=Josiah |editor-last1=Blackmore |editor-first2=Gregory S. |editor-last2=Hutcheson |date=12 August 1999 |publisher=[[Duke University Press]] |accessdate=19 September 2017 |isbn=978-0822323495}}</ref>{{rp|203}} Bernal was also mentioned in verse by the troubadours {{ill|Airas Peres Vuitoron|gl}}, [[João Baveca]] and Pedro (Pero) da Ponte.<ref name="Souto Cabo">{{cite journal |url=http://www.usc.es/revistas/index.php/verba/article/viewFile/877/848 |title=En Santiago, seend’ albergado en mia pousada |first=José António |last=Souto Cabo |publisher=[[Universidade de Santiago de Compostela]] |language=[[Galician language|Galician]] |journal=Verba |year=2012 |volume=39 |pages=278–280 of 263–298 |issn=0210-377X |accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>

It has been suggested in recent times by one author that Bernal may have had a reputation as a passive homosexual,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://csm.mml.ox.ac.uk/index.php?p=bib_view&rec=1611 |last=Blackmore |first=Josiah |title=Locating the Obscene: Approaching a Poetic Canon |journal=La corónica |volume=26.2 |year=1997–1998 |pages=9–16 |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> and may have been the same man as the one nicknamed "Bernal Fundado" (i.e. "Bernal the Split").<ref name=QI />{{rp|67}}<ref group=Note>A modern claim that someone in mediaeval times was or may have been homosexual should perhaps be treated with caution unless there is convincing contemporary evidence. In those days, an accusation that a rival or enemy was guilty of the sin and crime of [[Sodomy#Medieval Christendom|sodomy]] seems not to have been uncommon. For example, it was made in the 13th century during Bernal's lifetime against the [[Cathars]] in the [[Albigensian Crusade]] in the south of France.</ref>

==Works==
He is one of the earliest known ''[[wikt:xograr|xograr]]es'' or ''[[:wiktionary:pt:segrel|segreis]]'' (Galician troubadours).<ref name=AG /> Nineteen of his works have survived: ten ''{{ill|Cantiga de amor|lt=cantigas de amor|es}}'' (on the theme of [[courtly love]]), eight ''[[Cantiga de amigo|cantigas de amigo]]'', and one ''[[Tenso|tensón]]''.<ref name=AG /><ref name=Treccani>{{cite web |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/bernal-de-bonaval/ |title=Bernal "-àl" de Bonaval |website=[[Treccani]] |language=[[Italian language|Italian]] |accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref>{{refn|group=Note|A ''tensón'' was a debate in verse between poets. Bernal's ''tensón'' was between him and {{ill|Abril Pérez|gl}}.<ref name="Souto Cabo" /><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pA-yDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=bernal+de+bonaval+cantigas+de+amor&source=bl&ots=Zc5FTThtxD&sig=vHUV664RtU8PUx9iZLt4YWYUQ54&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjD69KB3q_WAhWK6xQKHTE_Crk4FBDoAQg5MAQ#v=onepage&q=bernal%20de%20bonaval%20cantigas%20de%20amor&f=false |title=Actas del XXIII Congreso Internacional de Lingüística y Filología Románica |editor-first=Fernando |editor-last=Sánchez Miret |language=[[Spanish language|Spanish]] |date=24–30 September 2001 |page=26 |publisher=[[Walter de Gruyter|Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG]] |accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref>}} He introduced popular motifs and realistic features into what had been a [[wikt:scholastic#Adjective|scholastic]] form of poetry.<ref name=Treccani /> He has been called "Villonesque",<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=OzArDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA349&lpg=PA349&dq=bernal+de+bonaval+cantigas+de+amor&source=bl&ots=prlMF_p2hF&sig=hj5GtoX9OG26416jmC3RuT7vj30&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjD69KB3q_WAhWK6xQKHTE_Crk4FBDoAQgnMAA#v=onepage&q=bernal%20de%20bonaval%20cantigas%20de%20amor&f=false |title=Routledge Revivals: Medieval Iberia (2003): An Encyclopedia |editor-first=E. Michael |editor-last=Gerli |page=349 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |origyear=2003 |date=2 June 2017 |isbn=978-1138062450 |accessdate=19 September 2017 }}</ref> even though [[François Villon]] lived two centuries later.

His songs have been preserved in the ''[[Cancioneiro da Vaticana]]'' (CV 660) and the ''[[Cancioneiro da Biblioteca Nacional]]'' (CBN 1003).<ref name=AG /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://albertosolana.wordpress.com/2017/04/01/31-bernal-de-bonaval-y-el-amor-platonico/ |title=31- Bernal de Bonaval y el amor platónico |website=albertosolana.wordpress.com |language=[[Galician language|Galician]] |date=1 April 2017 |accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>

==Legacy and critical reception==
Rúa de Bernal de Bonaval (a street) in Santiago de Compostela is named after him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.streetdir.es/ES/Galicia/Provincia-De-A-Coruna/Santiago-De-Compostela/Santiago-De-Compostela/Strassen/Rua-De-Bernal-De-Bonaval/ |title=Rúa de Bernal de Bonaval |website=streetdir.es |language=[[Spanish language|Spanish]] |accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref> In 1961, Brazilian scholar {{ill|Massaud Moisés|pt}} ranked him among the principal troubadours.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xcQYSXj0xN0C&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=bernardo+bonaval&source=bl&ots=mwa02cX3Aw&sig=SsQ_qybgvAUX8CYmIbNA9vOnbmw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTi5rsqbfWAhVbFMAKHf0uBxAQ6AEIgQEwEg#v=onepage&q=bernardo%20bonaval&f=false |title=A literatura portuguesa |first=Massaud |last=Moisés |page=24 |year=1961 |publisher={{ill|Cultrix|pt|Editora Pensamento-Cultrix}} |language=[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] |isbn=978-8531602313 |accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref> The 1971 album ''Cantigas de Amigos'' includes a duet between Portuguese artists [[Amália Rodrigues]] and [[Ary Dos Santos]] called "Vem esperar meu amigo".<ref>{{discogs release |id=6569656 |type=album |name=Amália Rodrigues, José Carlos Ary Dos Santos, Natália Correia{{snd}}''Cantigas de Amigos''}}</ref> It is a version of Bernal's ''cantiga de amigo'' "Ai, fremosinha, se ben ajades", named from its refrain rather than from its first line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cantigas.fcsh.unl.pt/versaomusical.asp?cdcant=1152&cdvm=133 |title=Vim esperar o meu amigo |website=[[Faculty of Social and Human Sciences]], [[Universidade Nova de Lisboa]] |language=[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] |accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref group=Note>That source does not name the author of the original text which it quotes, but it is identical to that of Bernal's "[[:s:pt:Ai, fremosinha, se ben ajades|Ai, fremosinha, se ben ajades]]".</ref> Spanish musician {{ill|Amancio Prada|es}} included his version of Bernal's "A dona que eu amo" on his 1984 album ''Leliadoura''.<ref>{{Discogs release |type=album |release=3908422 |name=Amancio Prada{{snd}}''Leliadoura''}}</ref> In 1985, Portuguese scholar Ribeiro Miranda published an academic paper analysing Bernal's importance.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://ler.letras.up.pt/uploads/ficheiros/artigo6031.pdf |title=O discursa poético de Bernal de Bonaval] |publisher=[[University of Porto]] |first=José Carlos |last=Ribeiro Miranda |pages=105–131 |year=1985 |journal=Revista da Faculdade de Letras: Línguas e Literaturas |series=II |volume=2 |language=[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] |accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref> In 1994, Galician writer [[Alfonso Daniel Rodríguez Castelao|Castelao]] named Bernal among the notable Galicians.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iEsxDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA285&lpg=PA285&dq=the+list+starts+with+roman+emperor+theodosius,+pope+damasus+I&source=bl&ots=FOca1QhDq9&sig=S2t1ipxHh7-N6iDXZ4AhR2uUIUo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjevqqR2LnWAhXGjJQKHVJcCwwQ6AEITDAJ#v=onepage&q=the%20list%20starts%20with%20roman%20emperor%20theodosius%2C%20pope%20damasus%20I&f=false |title=A Comparative History of Literatures in the Iberian Peninsula |volume=2 |page=285 |editor-first1=César |editor-last1=Domínguez |editor-first2=Anxo Abuín |editor-last2=González |editor-first3=Ellen |editor-last3=Sapega |date=20 October 2016 |publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company|John Benjamins]] |isbn=978-9027234650 }}</ref> In 2012, Galician scholar Souto Cabo called him "''uma das personalides poéticas mais célebres dos nossos cancioneros''" ("one of the most famous poets in our songbooks").<ref name="Souto Cabo" />

