'''Besmilr Brigham''' (September 28, 1913 - 2000) was an American poet and writer of short stories.
Brigham was born '''Bess Miller Moore''' in [[Pace, Mississippi]]. She graduated from Mary Hardin-Baylor College (now [[University of Mary Hardin–Baylor]]) in [[Belton, Texas]]. After that, she studied at the [[The New School|New School for Social Research]] in New York. In New York she met and married Roy Brigham.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}
According to the ''Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture'', "She came to prominence during the women’s movement of the 1960s, and her work is noted for its innovative structure, sound, and rhythm."<ref name="ark">{{cite web|title=Profile at|url=http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=1026|publisher=The Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>
Brigham is also known as Besmilr Moore Brigham. The Besmilr Women Writers Award is named after her.<ref name="bb">{{cite web|title=Besmilir Brigham Women Writers Award|url=http://lostroads.org/Brigham-Award.html|publisher=Lost Roads|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>
Brigham died of complications from [[Alzheimer's disease]] in 2000.<ref name="bb"/><ref name="ark"/>
==Works== * 1969. ''Agony dance: death of the dancing dolls'' (poetry) * 2000. ''Run through rock: selected short poems of Besmilr Brigham'' (C. D. Wright, ed.) * 1971. ''Heaved from the earth.'' (poetry)
==For further reading== * G.C. Waldrep, [http://www.kenyonreview.org/2014/10/chose-10/ "Why We Chose It: Two poems by besmilr brigham"], kenyonreview.org, October 6, 2014 * Martin, Meredith. “An Interview with Heloise Wilson”, ''The Aux-Arc Review 1'' (Fall 2002): 29–40 <!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --> * [https://www.poetryfoundation.org/harriet/2017/02/robert-yerachmiel-snyderman-looks-at-besmilr-brighams-fermenting-lyric "Robert Yerachmiel Snyderman Looks at Besmilr Brigham's Fermenting Lyric], poetryfoundation.org; accessed November 2, 2017.
