{{SS|John A. McGean}} was a steamship that operated on the Great Lakes in the early 1900s until she sank in the [[Great Lakes Storm of 1913]].
''John A. McGean'' was built in 1908 by the [[American Shipbuilding Company]] at their shipyard in [[Lorain, Ohio]].<ref name="book">{{cite book | title=Shipwrecks of the Great Lakes | publisher=Thunder Bay Press | author=Hancock, Paul | year=2001 | location=Holt, MI | pages=72 | isbn=1-882376--84-6}}</ref> She was {{convert|432|ft|m}} long, with a beam of {{convert|52|ft|m}} and a draft of {{convert|28|ft|m}}, and measured 5,100 [[gross tonnage|gross tons]].<ref name="book"/>
On November 7, 1913, ''John A. McGean'' was sailing into the Great Storm when she was sighted for the final time off [[Tawas Point Light]].<ref name="book"/> Sometime the following day, she sank with all 23 crew.<ref name="book"/> Her wreckage was not found until 1985, when it was discovered near [[Port Hope, Michigan]] with damage indicating that she had been swamped by a large wave.<ref name="book"/> Portions of the wreckage were found by a local doctor along the shoreline at [[Bayfield, Ontario]] in mid-November 1913. <ref> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Awful Marine Disaster on the Great Lakes |url= https://pubdocs.huroncounty.ca/weblink/3/doc/160063/Page1.aspx|work=The Signal |location=Goderich, Ontario |date=November 13, 1913 |access-date=April 19, 2018 }} </ref>
The body of chief engineer Calvin Smith was found near Black's Point, Ontario (just south of [[Goderich, Ontario]]) in late November 1913. Second cook D.M. Betts' remains were identified at the morgue in Goderich, Ontario via a photograph and details furnished by the Lake Carriers' Association. His remains were sent home to [[Girard, Pennsylvania]] on November 20, 1913. <ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Search Continues |url=https://pubdocs.huroncounty.ca/weblink/3/doc/160071/Page1.aspx |work=The Signal |location=Goderich, Ontario |date=November 20, 1913 |access-date=April 19, 2018 }} </ref>
