{{Infobox company | name = The Arlington Institute | logo = | type = [[501(c)(3)|non-profit]]| company_slogan = | foundation = 1989| location = [[Berkeley Springs, WV]]| key_people = [[John L. Petersen]], CEO & Chairman| industry = [[Futures techniques]]| num_employees = | products = [[Research]]| revenue = | homepage = {{url|http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org}} | }}
'''The Arlington Institute''' (or "'''TAI'''") is a [[501(c)(3)]] non-profit [[think tank]] specializing in predictive modeling of future events, that is, [[futures studies]]. It was founded in 1989 by former naval officer and military expert [[John L. Petersen]]<ref name="petersen_own_cv">{{cite web |title=John L. Peterson-CV |publisher=[[Arlington Institute]] |year= |accessdate=2014-03-05 |url=http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/john-l-petersen |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219223429/http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/john-l-petersen |archivedate=2014-02-19 |df= }}</ref> in [[Arlington, Virginia]].
==Aims== TAI believes society, science, ecology, and [[commerce]] are converging and that the issues that mankind is confronting are a product of how we live and think. As transition pioneers, TAI hopes to discover the early indicators of transition and provide solutions. The Arlington Institute is building an interactive web portal called The World's Biggest Problems. The site will allow people to collaborate on finding solutions to problems such as [[crisis (economic)|economic crisis]], [[species extinction]], [[peak oil]], [[climate change]], and [[water scarcity]].
==Leadership history== The Arlington Institute was founded by John L. Petersen in 1989.<ref name="history">{{cite web |title=History |url=http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/history |publisher=[[Arlington Institute]] |year= |accessdate=2014-03-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221083029/http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/history |archivedate=2014-02-21 |df= }}</ref> Petersen was a naval flight officer in the [[United States Navy]], and has worked at military institutions in the United States, including the [[National War College]], the [[Institute for National Security Studies (United States)|Institute for National Security Studies]], the [[Office of the Secretary of Defense]], and the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] at the [[White House]],<ref name="tai_board">{{cite web |title=Board of Directors |publisher=[[Arlington Institute]] |year=2010 |accessdate=2014-03-05 |url=http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/board-directors |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503151729/http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/board-directors |archivedate=2008-05-03 |df= }}</ref> and has had experience in business and non-profit organisations.<ref name="tai_board" /> Among the 2003 Board of Directors was [[Jack DuVall]], who had two years earlier created the [[International Center on Nonviolent Conflict]] together with [[Members of the Council on Foreign Relations#Board of directors|Council on Foreign Relations Board member]] [[Peter Ackerman]].<ref name="SUNYSB_Duvall">{{cite web |title=Limits and Opportunities of Nonviolent Resistance: Lessons from History and Current Conflicts |publisher=Students for Peace and Humanity, [[Stony Brook University]] |date=May 2003 |url=http://www.sinc.sunysb.edu/Clubs/sbdoves/announce.html |accessdate=2010-10-14 |archivedate=2010-10-14 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tU6N9GHa?url=http://www.sinc.sunysb.edu/Clubs/sbdoves/announce.html |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> In 2005, the Board of Directors of the Arlington Institute was chaired by John L. Petersen, and included Napier Collyns, George H. Kuper, David Martin, and another military expert, Owen Wormser. Wormser worked in the [[United States Air Force]], worked in the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]], and in 2005 was a visiting professor at the [[Joint Military Intelligence College]].<ref name="Arling_2005Board">{{cite web |authorlink=Arlington Institute |title=Board of Directors |publisher=[[Arlington Institute]] |year=2005 |url=http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/board-directors |accessdate=2010-10-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503151729/http://www.arlingtoninstitute.org/tai/board-directors |archivedate=2008-05-03 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
==Martin presentations in 2006, 2007== The Arlington Institute gained exposure in 2006 and 2007 when it hosted presentations made by Board member Dr. David Martin, also of M-CAM Inc., in which he detailed the dynamics contributing to the joint failure of credit, insurance, and [[monetary system]]s.{{citation needed|date=October 2010}}
